One: I like tormented characters.<br>
Two: I am incapable of playing someone truly evil. So, to be blunt, are most of you. I notice all these 'evil' people with loving spouses, etc...You don't seem to understand the nature of good and evil in fantasy. Neither, really, do many of the 'lighties'. It is REAL. It is not just some racial war. An evil person is EVIL and there is no doubt about it from any moral spectrum. A true follower of hate would gladly vivisect their spouse to gain personal power or sacrifice their children. They do not care about racial justice or equality-all others are to be used as tools for their personal power. They have few to no redeeming traits if they are truly evil. All they care about at base is themselves. So, by definition, we are almost all 'part-good' characters because I don't really think it would be interesting or fun to play as a truly evil character. In other words, don't criticize me for trying to humanize a DE. You do it all the time or you'd be playing banal incarnations of evil.<br>
<br>
Next: You seem to confuse Tehr's personality with that of the stereotypical dark elf renegade. He is not. He is 'well-intentioned with a good portion of good', really, rather then truly and utterly 'good', because while he believes in the 'good' moral code he is also bitter, vengeful, and at times quite bloodthirsty. While he does not commit evil acts against goodly people (hell, I run from faeries rather then fight them) he is not someone who sees compromise in alignment-evil is evil and good is good and there is no excuse for choosing evil no matter what horrible things happen to you. He does not worship a god-he is a confirmed skeptic and doesn't trust the limited paths of any of the goodly gods, though he respects the ideals of individual religions that he agrees with. He does not, in truth, have a lot of use for the divine beings, though this is due to his refusal to follow only one spectrum of what he considers good rather then any true disdain for the goodly and neutral gods. He sees things in terms of alignment rather then religion. <br>
<br>
Because he is a self-taught shadow knight (one of his siblings was the traditional rogue shadow knight and he listened to her incantations, then when he lost his left arm and had to get a prosthesis he was forced to use them to augment his fighting to make up for a somewhat more clumsy left arm.) and did not school himself in the philosophy of or ever take service with The Dead, he has no ties to them and as such I have NEVER done a shadow knight quest. On the other hand, because his memories of the incantations are imperfect, he has all sorts of bad side effects- among others having at times an almost irrational hatred of everything on the other side. Notably, by the way, he does not see Hate as something holy or unholy, but merely a more negative emotion. Basically, trying to compare him to our more stereotypical Tunare-loving darkie is not really fair.<br>
<br>
And finally. So the good-baddie thing is used a great deal. Who cares? As I have repeatedly said, all of our characters are stereotypical at heart. Let people play what they would like. Who are you to tell them what they can and can't roleplay? There are NPC examples of good-aligned evil creatures and evil-aligned good creatures. So why not for players?) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ansurfv>AnsurFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 433<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/31/03 9:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4677.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://us.f1.yahoofs.com/users/5c494d09/bc/Yahoo!+Photo+Album/Picture+40.jpg?pfLr8b.AhDvj2B36 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Double Standards</span><hr size=1> /sigh<br>
